The true position ofa mala tide possessor of solum alienum who builds upon it with his own materials is somewhat con· tradictorily stated in the Corpus iuris, but the two following conclusions appear to be warranted: (t) provided he does not injure the soil he may raze the building and remove his materials, though he cannot claim compensation for his outlay (even by advancing the exceptio doli, Cod 8. 10. 5), Dig. 6. r. 37, Cod. 3. 32. 5; the passage of Paulus in which the latter right is affirmed (Dig. 5. 3. 38) relates to an exceptional case, and under ordinary circumstances would be overridden by the latter part of this section, as well as by Dig. 6. 1. 37, Cod. 3. 32. 5 ; ib. 16.
